loadMacros(
    'PGstandard.pl',            'PGML.pl',
    'PGchoicemacros.pl',        'PGgraphmacros.pl',
    'extraAnswerEvaluators.pl', 'PGcourse.pl'
);

Context("Numeric")->variables->are(n => 'Real');

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$left   = random(80, 90, 5);
$a_ft   = random(5,  10, 1);
$a      = $a_ft * 12;
$r      = 100 - $left;
$b      = $left / 100;
$height = "$a ($b)^n";

$n      = random(8, 14, 1);
$exact2 = $a * $b**$n;
$ans2   = round($exact2);
$ans2l  = round(100 * $exact2) / 100;

$sol    = round((-log($a) / log($b)) * 1000) / 1000;
$ans3   = floor($sol) + 1;
$lower3 = $ans3 - 1;

BEGIN_PGML
A rubber ball is dropped onto a hard surface from a height of [$a_ft] feet,
and it bounces up and down.  At each bounce it rises to [$left]% of
the height from which it fell.

a) Find a formula for [`h(n)`], the height in inches reached by the ball on bounce [`n`].
  
    [` h(n) = `] [_]{$height}

b) How high will the ball bounce on the [` [$n]^{\mbox{th}} `] bounce?
  
    [` h = `] [_]{$exact2} inches

c) How many bounces before the ball rises no higher than an inch? [_]{$ans3} bounces

END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

a) The initial height is [$a_ft] feet, and since there are 12 inches in 1 foot, when [`n = 0`] we have 
    [```
    a = h(0) = [$a_ft]\;\text{ft} \times \frac{12\;\text{inches}}{1\;\text{ft}} = [$a]\;\text{inches} ```]

    Since after each bounce the ball rises to [$left][$PERCENT] of its
    previous height, we know the decay factor is [`b = [$b]`].  Therefore we
    have
    [``` h(n) = [$a]([$b])^n. ```]

b) We want to find the height when [`n = [$n]`], so we will evaluate [` h([$n]) `]:
    [``` h([[$n]]) = [$a] ([$b])^{[$n]} \approx [$ans2l] \mbox{ inches}. ```]

c) We are looking for the values of [`n`] for which [` h(n) \leq 1 `] inch, so we set [`h = 1`] and solve for [`n`]:
    [```\begin{aligned}
    h(n) &= 1 \\
    [$a]([$b])^n &= 1 \\
    ([$b])^n &= \frac{1}{[$a]} \\
    \log{([$b]^n)} &= \log{ \left( 1/[$a] \right) } \\
    n \, \log{([$b])} &= \log{([$a]^{-1})} \\
    n &= \frac{ - \log{([$a])}}{\log{([$b])}} \approx [$sol].
    \end{aligned}```]
    So after [$lower3] bounces, the ball will rise just over 1 inch, and after
    [$ans3] bounces it will rise to a height just under 1 inch.  Thus after
[$ans3] bounces the ball will rise less than 1 inch.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

